{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12866"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.63,0.04,0.2,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89424"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1780"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"},{"type":"tags","id":"3426"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8259"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 66-year-old woman presents to the General Practitioner with a three-month history of fatigue, night sweats, and 7 kg weight loss. She has no significant past medical history and is on no regular medications. On examination, she is pale, with a pulse rate of 95/min, blood pressure 115/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are palpable cervical, axillary, and inguinal lymph nodes of 1-2 cm in size. Her spleen is palpable 3 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 92 g/L (135-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal white blood cell count 40 x 10^9/L (4.5-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 110 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is a predominance of small, mature lymphocytes with round nuclei and scant cytoplasm on the peripheral blood smear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tests is the most helpful to confirm a malignant (clonal) pathology in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemoglobin electrophoresis","Flow cytometry of peripheral blood","Direct antiglobulin test","Serum protein electrophoresis","Serum free light chain"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis elderly patient presents with three months of constitutional symptoms. She was found to have generalised lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly. These features are consistent with a lymphoproliferative disorder (LPD). Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL) is the most common leukaemia in adults, particularly elderly adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe peripheral blood smear typically shows many small, mature lymphocytes with round nuclei and scant cytoplasm. \u003Cstrong\u003EFlow cytometry of peripheral blood\u003C/strong\u003E can confirm the diagnosis by identifying monoclonal B-lymphocytes with a typical immunophenotypic profile. Anaemia and thrombocytopenia are common due to either marrow infiltration by CLL or immune-mediated destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose haemoglobinopathies (e.g., sickle cell disease) and thalassaemias. It would not help diagnose a lymphoproliferative disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EDirect antiglobulin test\u003C/strong\u003E (DAT) is used to detect antibodies bound to red blood cells, which can indicate autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. While autoimmune haemolytic anaemia can occur in CLL, the DAT would not help establish the underlying diagnosis of a lymphoproliferative disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E (SPEP) is a laboratory test that separates proteins in the blood based on their electrical charge and size. It is most commonly used to detect monoclonal proteins in plasma cell dyscrasia (e.g., multiple myeloma). While paraproteins may be seen in CLL, SPEP is not routinely required for the diagnosis. This case is not consistent with multiple myeloma due to the blood film findings (i.e., lymphocytosis). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum free light chain\u003C/strong\u003E analysis is primarily used in the diagnosis and monitoring of plasma cell disorders like multiple myeloma. It would not be helpful in confirming the diagnosis of CLL or other LPDs where the abnormal cells are primarily lymphocytes rather than plasma cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL), a low-grade lymphoproliferative disorder, most commonly affects elderly patients.","It typically presents with constitutional symptoms, lymphadenopathy, and hepatosplenomegaly.","CLL is most commonly diagnosed by flow cytometry of blood, which shows monoclonal B-lymphocytes with typical immunophenotypic profile."],"references":["Hallek M, Cheson BD, Catovsky D, Caligaris-Cappio F, Dighiero G, D\u00f6hner H, et al. iwCLL guidelines for diagnosis, indications for treatment, response assessment, and supportive management of CLL. Blood. 2018 Jun 21;131(25):2745\u201360."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89424"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12866"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89424"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T10:52:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T10:52:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5309"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106938"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":